	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong{\textgreater}Co-PIs{\textless}/strong{\textgreater}: Matthew Thomas Miller (University of Maryland, College Park), Maxim G. Romanov (University of Vienna), Sarah Bowen Savant (Aga Khan University\&mdash;ISMC, London).{\textless}/p{\textgreater}

{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}em{\textgreater}Open Islamicate Texts Initiative{\textless}/em{\textgreater} ({\textless}strong{\textgreater}OpenITI{\textless}/strong{\textgreater}, see {\textless}a href="https://iti-corpus.github.io/"{\textgreater}https://iti-corpus.github.io/{\textless}/a{\textgreater})\&nbsp;is a multi-institutional effort to construct the first machine-actionable scholarly corpus of premodern Islamicate texts. Led by researchers at the Aga Khan University, Institute for the Study of Muslim Civilisations (AKU-ISMC), University of Vienna (UV), Leipzig University (LU), and the Roshan Institute for Persian Studies at the University of Maryland (College Park) and an interdisciplinary advisory board of leading digital humanists and Islamic, Persian, and Arabic studies scholars, {\textless}strong{\textgreater}OpenITI{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} aims to provide the essential textual infrastructure in Arabic, Persian and other Islamicate languages for new forms of textual analysis and digital scholarship. In the process, OpenITI will enable new synergies between Digital Humanities and the inter-related Islamicate fields of Islamic, Persian, and Arabic Studies. In addition to support from the researchers\&rsquo; home institutions, it is supported by funding from the {\textless}a href="https://erc.europa.eu/"{\textgreater}European Research Council{\textless}/a{\textgreater} under the European Union\&rsquo;s Horizon 2020 research and innovation programme, awarded to the {\textless}a href="http://kitab-project.org/"{\textgreater}KITAB{\textless}/a{\textgreater} project (Grant Agreement No. 772989, PI Sarah Bowen Savant) and the {\textless}a href="https://www.qnl.qa/en"{\textgreater}Qatar National Library{\textless}/a{\textgreater}.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}

{\textless}p{\textgreater}Currently, {\textless}strong{\textgreater}OpenITI{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} contains almost exclusively Arabic texts, which were first assembled into a corpus within the {\textless}strong{\textgreater}OpenArabic{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} project, developed first at Tufts University (at {\textless}em{\textgreater}The Perseus Project{\textless}/em{\textgreater}, 2013\&ndash;2015) and then at Leipzig University (at the Alexander von Humboldt Chair for Digital Humanities, 2015\&ndash;2017)\&mdash;in both cases with the support and under the patronage of Prof. Gregory Crane. The much more limited number of Persian texts were compiled during 2015\&ndash;2016 in the Persian Digital Library (PDL) pilot (see {\textless}a href="https://persdigumd.github.io/PDL/"{\textgreater}Persian Digital Library by PersDigUMD{\textless}/a{\textgreater}) at Roshan Institute for Persian Studies at the University of Maryland. These texts have not been made fully compatible with OpenITI mARkdown yet and will be made fully available in next releases.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}

